James de Villiers, News 24 Robyn Pearce who was killed in an apartment in Sea Point the past weekend. (Facebook) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Cape Town &ndash; Family close to Robyn Pearce, 20, who was killed in her mother&rsquo;s flat last weekend say that they are still traumatised by the incident.&nbsp;Robyn was a second year Humanities student at Stellenbosch University.&nbsp;&ldquo;We are just over the death of her father 5 years ago and now this. It is all so completely unexpected,&rdquo; Bronwyn Pearce, Robyn&rsquo;s aunt, told News24 on Sunday.&nbsp;&ldquo;It has all been a lot for the family the past week dealing with police and this tragedy.&rdquo;Robyn&rsquo;s body was taken to Durban last week and she was laid to rest on Saturday. The family plans to hold a memorial for Robyn in Stellenbosch early next year.&nbsp;Incorrect facts&nbsp;Bronwyn has criticised the media for false reporting.&nbsp;&ldquo;We are frustrated that the basic facts aren&rsquo;t reported correctly,&rdquo; Bronwyn said.&nbsp;&ldquo;For example, Robyn was visiting her mom&rsquo;s flat in Sea Point and not a friend&rsquo;s flat as is being reported.&rdquo;&nbsp;&ldquo;Her (Robyn) body was also discovered on Friday the 2nd of December, and not the Saturday.&rdquo;Bronwyn could not give any additional information on Robyn&rsquo;s murder and said that she hopes someone will soon come forward with additional information.&nbsp;&ldquo;She could&rsquo;ve been killed by a burglar, we just don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; Bronwyn added.&nbsp;News24 reported on Sunday that Robyn was stabbed in an apartment in Sea Point. According to Western Cape Police spokesperson Captain Federick van Wyk no arrests have been made.&nbsp; 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.